{"title_page": "Brad Bradford", "text_new": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Brad Bradford\n| image        = Brad Bradford - 2018 (43702767760) (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Bradford in 2018\n| office1      = [[Toronto City Council]]lor for [[Beaches-East York|Ward 19 (Beaches-East York)]]\n| term_start1  = December 1, 2018\n| term_end1    = \n| preceded1  = [[Janet Davis]] <small>(Ward 31)</small><br />{{nowrap|[[Mary-Margaret McMahon]] <small>(Ward 32)</small>}}\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1986|8|1}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cambridge]], [[Ontario]]\n| alma_mater   = [[York University]], [[University of Waterloo]]\n| residence    = Toronto\n| religion     = \n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| spouse       = \n| occupation   = Urban Planner\n| website      = {{URL|https://www.bradbradford.ca/}}\n}}\n\n'''Brad Bradford''' ({{audio|help=no|Bradbradfordname.ogg|Listen}}) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician was elected to the [[Toronto City Council]] in the [[2018 Toronto municipal election|2018 municipal election]].<ref name=\"wins\">[https://www.thestar.com/news/toronto-election/2018/10/22/brad-bradford-wins-in-close-race.html \"Brad Bradford wins Ward 19, Beaches\u2014East York, in close race\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 22, 2018.</ref> He represents [[Beaches\u2014East York|Ward 19 (Beaches\u2014East York)]].\n\nBradford was appointed as a member of the Board of the Toronto Transit Commission by Toronto City Council on December 13, 2018.<ref>http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2019.ST1.1</ref> He sits on two City Council Committees, the Budget Committee and the Planning and Housing Committee.<ref>https://www.toronto.ca/city-government/council/members-of-council/councillor-ward-19/</ref><ref>https://www.ttc.ca/About_the_TTC/Commission_reports_and_information/index.jsp</ref>\n\nPrior to his election, Bradford worked as an urban planner in the Chief Planner's Office at the City of Toronto.<ref name=wins/> He  holds a bachelor of environmental studies in urban and regional environments from [[York University]], and a masters in urban planning from the [[University of Waterloo]].<ref name=\"wins\" /> \n==Electoral record==\nCouncillor Bradford was endorsed by Mayor [[John Tory]], Deputy Mayor [[Ana Bail\u00e3o]], former liberal MPP [[Arthur Potts (politician)|Arthur Potts]], former Councillor [[Mary-Margaret McMahon]]<ref name=\"bradbradford.ca\">https://www.bradbradford.ca/about_me</ref> and former Chief Planner and Mayoral Candidate [[Jennifer Keesmaat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bradbradford.ca/campaign_updates|title=Campaign Updates|website=Brad Bradford|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> These endorsements helped Bradford defeat candidate [[Matthew Kellway]], former NDP MP for the Beaches East York Riding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4584494/toronto-election-2018-new-councillors/|title=Toronto election 2018: Meet your new city councillors - Toronto {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2018-10-23|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\nBradford ran as a progressive candidate, his background in the planner's office cited as proof of his city building experience.<ref name=\"bradbradford.ca\"/>\n\n===2019===\nBradford's first budget was contentious as [[Shelley Carroll]] and [[Mike Layton]] presented last minute motions intended to gather information beyond the budget process. He voted against all of these motions which distressed concerned parties.<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2019/02/20/budget-committee-rejects-councillors-attempt-to-scrap-ttc-fare-increase-and-improve-library-hours.html</ref>\n\n===Electoral Reform===\nCouncillor Bradford brought a motion to City Council on [[term limits]], which was seconded by Ana Bail\u00e3o and referred to the Special Committee on Governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/02/21/proposal-for-toronto-council-term-limits-punted.html|title=Proposal for Toronto council term limits punted {{!}} The Star|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> The motion cited numerous examples <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2019/gv/comm/communicationfile-91607.pdf|title=Term Limits Special Committee on Governance Presentation}}</ref> where term limits facilitated a more representative council makeup by eliminating [[incumbent advantage]].<ref>https://www.bradbradford.ca/term_limits</ref> He was opposed by left-leaning Councillor [[Gord Perks]] (\"The last thing a government should do is tell people who they are allowed to vote for\") and right-leaning councillor [[Jim Karygiannis]] (\"If our constituents don\u2019t want us they can kick us out\").<ref>https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/rookie-councillor-to-put-forth-a-motion-on-term-limits-at-next-city-council-meeting-1.4270015</ref>\n\nThe motion was deferred indefinitely, but if successful it would have needed provincial approval in order to be passed into [[City of Toronto Act|law]].<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/rookie-councillor-brings-back-term-limits-debate-calls-it-opportunity-to-bring-fresh-faces-1.5000342</ref>\n\n=== Increasing Transparency at City Hall ===\nBradford also introduced a motion at City Council to explore the use of Hansard to increase transparency and engagement at City Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2019.MM6.15|title=Hansard Motion}}</ref> This motion was applauded by academics, community organizers and the press[?].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Toronto City Councillors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradford, Brad}}\n[[Category:Canadian urban planners]]\n[[Category:Toronto city councillors]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Canadian politician|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name         = Brad Bradford\n| image        = Brad Bradford - 2018 (43702767760) (cropped).jpg\n| imagesize    = \n| caption      = Bradford in 2018\n| office1      = [[Toronto City Council]]lor for [[Beaches-East York|Ward 19 (Beaches-East York)]]\n| term_start1  = December 1, 2018\n| term_end1    = \n| preceded1  = [[Janet Davis]] <small>(Ward 31)</small><br />{{nowrap|[[Mary-Margaret McMahon]] <small>(Ward 32)</small>}}\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1986|8|1}}\n| birth_place  = [[Cambridge]], [[Ontario]]\n| alma_mater   = [[York University]], [[University of Waterloo]]\n| residence    = Toronto\n| religion     = \n| nationality  = [[Canadians|Canadian]]\n| spouse       = \n| occupation   = Urban Planner\n| website      = {{URL|https://www.bradbradford.ca/}}\n}}\n\n'''Brad Bradford''' ({{audio|help=no|Bradbradfordname.ogg|Listen}}) is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] politician, born Bradford Bradford, was elected to the [[Toronto City Council]] in the [[2018 Toronto municipal election|2018 municipal election]].<ref name=\"wins\">[https://www.thestar.com/news/toronto-election/2018/10/22/brad-bradford-wins-in-close-race.html \"Brad Bradford wins Ward 19, Beaches\u2014East York, in close race\"]. ''[[Toronto Star]]'', October 22, 2018.</ref> He represents [[Beaches\u2014East York|Ward 19 (Beaches\u2014East York)]].\n\nBradford was appointed as a member of the Board of the Toronto Transit Commission by Toronto City Council on December 13, 2018.<ref>http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2019.ST1.1</ref> He sits on two City Council Committees, the Budget Committee and the Planning and Housing Committee.<ref>https://www.toronto.ca/city-government/council/members-of-council/councillor-ward-19/</ref><ref>https://www.ttc.ca/About_the_TTC/Commission_reports_and_information/index.jsp</ref>\n\nPrior to his election, Bradford worked as an urban planner in the Chief Planner's Office at the City of Toronto.<ref name=wins/> He  holds a bachelor of environmental studies in urban and regional environments from [[York University]], and a masters in urban planning from the [[University of Waterloo]].<ref name=\"wins\" /> \n==Electoral record==\nCouncillor Bradford was endorsed by Mayor [[John Tory]], Deputy Mayor [[Ana Bail\u00e3o]], former liberal MPP [[Arthur Potts (politician)|Arthur Potts]], former Councillor [[Mary-Margaret McMahon]]<ref name=\"bradbradford.ca\">https://www.bradbradford.ca/about_me</ref> and former Chief Planner and Mayoral Candidate [[Jennifer Keesmaat]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bradbradford.ca/campaign_updates|title=Campaign Updates|website=Brad Bradford|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> These endorsements helped Bradford defeat candidate [[Matthew Kellway]], former NDP MP for the Beaches East York Riding.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/4584494/toronto-election-2018-new-councillors/|title=Toronto election 2018: Meet your new city councillors - Toronto {{!}} Globalnews.ca|date=2018-10-23|website=globalnews.ca|language=en|access-date=2019-04-17}}</ref>\n\nBradford ran as a progressive candidate, his background in the planner's office cited as proof of his city building experience.<ref name=\"bradbradford.ca\"/>\n\n===2019===\nBradford's first budget was contentious as [[Shelley Carroll]] and [[Mike Layton]] presented last minute motions intended to gather information beyond the budget process. He voted against all of these motions which distressed concerned parties.<ref>https://www.thestar.com/news/city_hall/2019/02/20/budget-committee-rejects-councillors-attempt-to-scrap-ttc-fare-increase-and-improve-library-hours.html</ref>\n\n===Electoral Reform===\nCouncillor Bradford brought a motion to City Council on [[term limits]], which was seconded by Ana Bail\u00e3o and referred to the Special Committee on Governance.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/2019/02/21/proposal-for-toronto-council-term-limits-punted.html|title=Proposal for Toronto council term limits punted {{!}} The Star|website=thestar.com|language=en|access-date=2019-04-18}}</ref> The motion cited numerous examples <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.toronto.ca/legdocs/mmis/2019/gv/comm/communicationfile-91607.pdf|title=Term Limits Special Committee on Governance Presentation}}</ref> where term limits facilitated a more representative council makeup by eliminating [[incumbent advantage]].<ref>https://www.bradbradford.ca/term_limits</ref> He was opposed by left-leaning Councillor [[Gord Perks]] (\"The last thing a government should do is tell people who they are allowed to vote for\") and right-leaning councillor [[Jim Karygiannis]] (\"If our constituents don\u2019t want us they can kick us out\").<ref>https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/rookie-councillor-to-put-forth-a-motion-on-term-limits-at-next-city-council-meeting-1.4270015</ref>\n\nThe motion was deferred indefinitely, but if successful it would have needed provincial approval in order to be passed into [[City of Toronto Act|law]].<ref>https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/rookie-councillor-brings-back-term-limits-debate-calls-it-opportunity-to-bring-fresh-faces-1.5000342</ref>\n\n=== Increasing Transparency at City Hall ===\nBradford also introduced a motion at City Council to explore the use of Hansard to increase transparency and engagement at City Hall.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://app.toronto.ca/tmmis/viewAgendaItemHistory.do?item=2019.MM6.15|title=Hansard Motion}}</ref> This motion was applauded by academics, community organizers and the press[?].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Toronto City Councillors}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradford, Brad}}\n[[Category:Canadian urban planners]]\n[[Category:Toronto city councillors]]\n[[Category:University of Waterloo alumni]]\n[[Category:York University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n", "name_user": "Sikander", "label":